@Node Gadgets "Main part: CD32-Emulator-Gadgets"

                   @{b}Setting the CD32-Emulator preferences@{ub}
                   -------------------------------------

Select the gadget you want to know more about:

    @{" No FastMem         " link NoFastMem}
    @{" No Instr. Cache    " link NoInstCache}
    @{" No Data Cache      " link NoDataCache}
    @{" Vector Base 0      " link VectorBase0}
    @{" No Volume Control  " link NoVolControl}
    @{" Emulate Controller " link EmulContr}
    @{" Use 68040.library  " link 68040Lib}
    @{" Load Workbench     " link LoadWb}
    @{" DOS Device         " link DOSDev}
    @{" Blocks Buffer      " link BlocksBuffer}
    @{" Delay p. Block     " link Delay}
    @{" Max Volume         " link MaxVol}
    @{" Language           " link Language}
@Endnode

@Node NoFastMem "No FastMem"

@{b}No FastMem@{ub}
==========

Enabling NoFastMem will disable all Fast Memory in your Amiga. 
You should only enable this switch, if the game you want to play 
requires this. If the graphic and/or sound of a game is corrupted, 
try this option.
@Endnode

@Node NoInstCache "No Instr. Cache"

@{b}No Instr. Cache@{ub}
===============

This will disable the instruction cache of the processor. This option
should rarely be necessary. If you encounter that a game is
running too fast, you should try this option.
@Endnode

@Node NoDataCache "No Data Cache"

@{b}No Data Cache@{ub}
=============

This will disable the data cache of the processor. If you encounter
that a game is running too fast, you should try this option.
@Endnode

@Node VectorBase0 "Vector Base 0"

@{b}Vector Base 0@{ub}
=============

This option is only necessary if you started the game from Workbench.
Some games don't work at all if this option isn't enabled.
@Endnode

@Node NoVolControl "No Volume Control"

@{b}No Volume Control@{ub}
=================

This will disable the attenuation control of the CD32-Emulator.
If the digital audio produced by a game CD cannot be heard or
the game "hangs", try enabling this flag.
@Endnode

@Node EmulContr "Emulate Controller"

@{b}Emulate Controller@{ub}
==================

If this is enabled, the CD32 Game Controller will be emulated with
the keyboard. You shouldn't select this, if you have a CD32 Game
Controller connected to your Amiga. You may connect a one or two
button joystick and use the keyboard to access the additional keys.
Emulation keys are:

-> Joypad direction:
   Numbers 1,2,3,4,6,7,8,9 on numeric keypad and cursor keys

-> Reverse:
   [ and / on numeric keypad

-> Forward:
   ] and * on numeric keypad

-> Green button:
   F1 and F6

-> Yellow button:
   F2 and F7

-> Red button:
   F3, F8 and Space, Enter and 0 on numeric keypad

-> Blue button:
   F4, F9 and Del on numeric keypad

-> Play/Pause button:
   F5 and F10

@{b}Note:@{ub} It is possible that some games do not work if controller
      emulation is enabled!
@Endnode

@Node 68040Lib "Use 68040.library"

@{b}Use 68040.library@{ub}
=================

Most games will not work if Commodores 68040.library is used.
But if it is possible to use this library, system performance will be
greatly increased. This @{b}only applies to machines with 68040 processors@{ub},
of course.
@Endnode

@Node LoadWb "Load Workbench"

@{b}Load Workbench@{ub}
==============

Some games will probably not run correctly if there is no Workbench
process running. We know only of the game "Morph" which requires this
flag to be selected. Usually you should leave this off.
@Endnode

@Node DOSDev "DOS Device"

@{b}DOS Device@{ub}
==========

Here you define the CD-ROM drive, where the CD32 emulation should happen.
@Endnode

@Node BlocksBuffer "Blocks Buffer"

@{b}Blocks Buffer@{ub}
=============

The CD32-Emulator has a built in prefetch cache. Here you can set the size
of this cache (1 Block equals 2048 Bytes). The optimum value differs
depending on your configuration (Amiga model, hostadapter, CD-ROM drive).
You have to experiment to find a good value. The rule is:
Keep the value as small as possible, but big enough, that
off-the-disk-animations run smoothly.
For TandemCD/CD1200 the optimum value is 4, most SCSI drives work
best with a value of 2.
@Endnode

@Node Delay "Delay p. Block"

@{b}Delay p. Block@{ub}
==============

If you specify a value other than zero, a delay will be added between
reading different sectors. This is important, if you have a CD-ROM drive
which is faster than the original CD32.
If you have a single or double speed drive, leave this value to zero.
If you have a faster (triple, quad speed) drive, you should enter a value
between 50 and 100 here. You must experiment for best results, as the
correct timing will be affected by your system performance.
@Endnode

@Node MaxVol "Max Volume"

@{b}Max Volume@{ub}
==========

Here you can specify the maximum level the CD sound should have
during gameplay.
@Endnode

@Node Language

@{b}Language@{ub}
========

Here you can select your preferred language for multi-language games.
@Endnode

@Node Methods "Main part: Finding optimal settings"

                        @{b}How to find optimal settings@{ub}
                        ----------------------------

The best way of finding optimal settings is to start with a
"conservative" one:

This would be: - "No FastMem=ON"
               - "Vector Base 0=ON"
               - "Use 68040.library=OFF"
               - "No Instr. Cache=ON"
               - "No Data Cache=ON"
               - "Emulate Controller=OFF"
               - "No Volume Control=ON"
               - "Load Workbench=OFF"

If you like the game, you first should try to activate the instruction
cache ("No Instr. Cache=OFF"). If everything was fine you can try
to use "No FastMem=OFF" and "Use 68040.library=ON".
If you're using an IDE-ATAPI Sony CDU-55E CD-ROM drive (e. g. with
the A4000_atapi.device by "Elaborate Bytes"), "No Volume Control=ON"
has to be selected.

To get more concrete information about the gadgets, please
look at the @{" General information " link Gadgets} - part!
@Endnode

